==English==
=== Etymology ===
Old English loosely translating into modern-day English to mean ''Let woe rise up against'', formerly used to decry a person's actions. Gramatically, it is a phrase in the [[subjunctive]] mood.

===Verbal phrase===
'''[[woe]] [[betide]]'''
# bad things will happen to
#:Example: '' '''Woe betide''' you if I find you adding silly words to Wiktionary again!''